Love is not a mystery... at least not to renowned psychologist and UW alum John Gottman. When he looks at a marriage and predicts whether it will or won't end in divorce, Gottman is right 94 percent of the time. His work is wildly popular, and with good reason: If half of today's marriages go sour, who wouldn't grab onto an easy, evidence-based antidote?

status_message: A campus wouldn't be a campus without bricks and mortar, without indoor spaces to teach and learn and conduct research ‚Äî especially when winter hits hard across the Midwest. But at UW-Madison, we also place great value on outdoor spaces, those spots where nature has dibs. One-third of our main campus, in fact, is dedicated to the Lakeshore Nature Preserve, acres protected and preserved for green space and the natural order of things. Other parts of the main campus and university property also host spots where creatures of all kinds can make themselves at home. Jeff Miller, senior photographer in University Communications, has captured just some of them in this collection of photos: news.wisc.edu/23839
link_name: Wild, Wild Campus: A visual sampling of the creatures among us

Members of the UW-Madison Community,

You are receiving this Crime Alert message as part of UW-Madison's commitment to providing campus-area crime information.

On November 13, 2013 at 5:51pm an armed robbery occurred at West Washington Avenue and Regent Street. The victim was walking when the suspect confronted him with a knife.  The suspect was described as a white male, approximately 20 years of age, average build, 5'9"-6'1", wearing a dark windbreaker-type jacket, jeans, and a dark stocking hat.  Suspect displayed a knife before taking the victim's laptop and cash. The suspect fled on foot on the bike path towards the Kohl Center and the victim was not injured.

Students and staff are reminded, as a general safety rule, to be aware of your surroundings at all times, especially at night.   At night it is best to walk in groups or make use of the University's Safe Walk services ‚Äì call 262-5000.  If ever confronted by an individual with a weapon, give up your property and don't resist.  If you see anyone exhibiting suspicious behavior or criminal behavior, immediately call 911.

The City of Madison Police Department is investigating this case.  If anyone has any information about the crime listed above contact the Madison Police Department at (608) 266-4948.  If you witness other crimes on campus, please call the UW-Madison Police Department at (608) 264-COPS.

WiscAlert-Around 6:27 p.m. on Wednesday, UWPD received reports of shots fired in the 100 block of Langdon Street near campus in downtown Madison. UWPD responded along with Madison Police.
 
UWPD notified the campus community through a series of WiscAlerts text messages, emails, web and social media posts, beginning at 6:32 p.m.
 
A suspect was initially believed to be headed west down the Lakeshore Path.
 
A person of interest matching the suspect description was detained at 6:42 p.m. by UWPD.
 
A thorough search of campus from Lake Street to Lot 34 along the lakefront was conducted.
 
No one was injured, and as of 8:50 p.m. there is believed to be no ongoing danger to the campus community. A series of all-clear WiscAlerts was sent.
 
UWPD and Madison Police continue to investigate the situation. If you have any information, call Madison Area Crime Stoppers at (608) 266-6014. Callers can remain anonymous.
WiscAlert: You do not need to shelter in place any longer. Please avoid the area along the lake from Lake Street to just west of Lot 34 as you will see police activity in the area.
WiscAlert:Suspect in shots fired at 130 Langdon: Description male/black wearing black clothing with a black/white baseball cap,black jacket,dark backpack.
WiscAlert- Update: Police continue to search west of Memorial Union along lake path for Langson St shots fired suspect. Shelter in Place avoid area.

WISCALERT: UWPD has released a description of the suspect: Male, black wearing black clothing with a black/white baseball cap, black jacket, dark backpack. 

All are advised to shelter in place and stay indoors in the central campus area. More information will be posted as it becomes available.

WISCALERT:UWPD is responding to reports of shots fired on Langdon Street, with the suspect heading down the lakeshore path in the direction of the Lakeshore residence halls. 

All are advised to stay indoors and shelter in place. More information will be posted here and on http://wisc.edu as it becomes available.

status_message: Today is the day: UW-Madison Day at the State Fair! Come visit us this afternoon or track all the fun at http://social.wisc.edu

Tomorrow's the day -- will you join us for UW-Madison Day at the Wisconsin State Fair?
 
You'll be able to see Bucky, hold the axe, get your cream puff on, and most importantly: help a student in need. Donate approved school supplies for Milwaukee Public Schools and receive $4 off admission: www.statefair.wisc.edu/school-supplies.html

Here's some advice: "Live every week like it's Shark Week."

Luke Polshek definitely got the memo. A Badger could take on a bull shark in Fiji any day.

It's back and looking better than ever: Wisconsin Alumni's 6th annual Red Shirt is now available online and at University Bookstore locations. Proceeds benefit the Great People Scholarship: www.uwalumni.com/theredshirt

How many Red Shirts are in your closet?

The Carson Gulley Center has been a UW-Madison Dining landmark since 1926, but you've never seen it like this. Opening after a year of renovation, the new Carson's brings a focus to community and sustainability while honoring its namesake, trailblazer and renowned chef Carson Gulley.

Read more about Gulley's remarkable life: www.news.wisc.edu/17799

Can't wait for the Wisconsin Football season opener to get that gameday experience? You don't have to.

August is full of events at Camp Randall for all ages -- click on the link and mark your calendars!

http://www.uwbadgers.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/072313aac.html

Stop and smell the... rotting flesh? 

That's right. Our Titan Arum, or "corpse flower" plant, is set to bloom any day at D.C. Smith Greenhouse. Come take a whiff (if you're brave enough) like so many others have in years past. 

Stay up-to-date at http://dcsmithgreenhouse.cals.wisc.edu

Colin Harris' Badger spirit is as tall as the Eiffel Tower.

Move-in info available here: http://go.wisc.edu/moveinday

Tim Gattenby, an upbeat coordinator in the Dept. of Kinesiology, works hard to make biking accessible to children with disabilities. 

His motto: "We leave our perceptions of limitations outside these doors." 

Read on: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21977

We couldn't be more proud of all the Badgers who took part in the BTN Big 10K in Chicago today. There's another thing we're very proud of near the giant foam finger -- see it?

BuzzFeed shared this photo today of some 1967 co-eds laughing it up in a UW-Madison Residence Halls Peanuts-themed room.

UW-Madison Day at the State Fair is coming August 7 -- what kinds of food are you looking to try at the fair?

Dr. Yoshihiro Kawaoka and his team have made global news with their research on the H7N9 avian flu virus.

But did you know his work with another strain, H5N1, was referenced in Dan Brown's newest book, "Inferno?"

Learn more about her here: http://chancellor.wisc.edu

What's the coolest thing you've ever made to show off your Badger pride?

Wisconsin parents: Do you remember the heel-prick blood test your baby received just after birth? 

Did you know that the  Wisconsin State Laboratory of Hygiene screens 70,000 newborns every year for rare diseases? We're celebrating 50 years of this remarkable public health service: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21941

Exactly 150 years after the Battle of Gettysburg, we're remembering all of the Wisconsin soldiers who trained to fight for the Union at our own Camp Randall in Madison.

Happy Independence Day, #Wisconsin!

It's the trip of a lifetime: UW-Madison UW-Madison School of Journalism & Mass Communication grad Erin Luhmann is in Timbuktu, Mali tonight as part of a reporting trip she won to travel with Nicholas Kristof of The New York Times

She plans to raise awareness of African poverty and global health. What would you cover on a trip around the world? http://go.wisc.edu/trip

The summer heat brings out countless types of bugs in Wisconsin, and Phil Pelliteri can name just about all of them. Working out of the UW-Madison Insect Diagnostic Lab, Pelliteri identifies any insect that is sent, e-mailed, or described over the phone, making him one of our most famous experts. 

Which bugs are you seeing the most this summer?

UW-Madison jazz professor Richard Davis played bass behind music greats like Sinatra and Springsteen; now, he is being honored as a great in his own right. The National Endowment for the Arts just named Davis as one of four NEA 2014 Jazz Masters, considered the highest honor among living jazz musicians: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21911
Like our photos? See more at http://instagram.com/uwmadison

Monica Minor is showing her pride from the legendary Inca ruins of Machu Picchu, Peru. #onwisconsin

Have you noticed the new addition to the Lake Mendota shoreline? Yesterday evening, incoming Chancellor Blank and the Wisconsin Alumni Association dedicated the Goodspeed Family Pier at Lake Street.

This scenic lake in Chile looks like a vacation destination, but in a matter of weeks it could be the site of a volcanic eruption big enough to affect the entire planet. Despite the danger, a team from UW-Madison's geoscience department is here doing research. Read more about their progress and experiences: http://www.news.wisc.edu/chile_volcano/

What part of the world are you most interested in studying?

We're creating a new flavor of Babcock ice cream to welcome Chancellor Rebecca Blank to campus, and we need your taste buds and imagination. Comment with ideas for flavors and titles‚Äîthe winner will be produced in September!

Tonight: A man wrongly convicted of murder is freed and a paralyzed surgeon returns to the operating room, both with help from UW-Madison students. Catch both these stories on Forward Motion, 9 p.m. CST on the Big Ten Network.

House of Pain released "Jump Around" on this date in 1992. 

The New York Times has a great explanation of how we came to adopt it. http://go.wisc.edu/jump

Is there a better tradition in college football?

Badgers have the brains AND the brawn: BuzzFeed just listed UW-Madison as one of the top 10 most academically and athletically dominant colleges in America. See the full list here: http://go.wisc.edu/buzzfeed

What do you think of where we landed?

Legendary preservationist John Muir spent five terms in Madison in 1861, before departing for the "University of the Wilderness."

He went on to found The Sierra Club and create  Yosemite National Park. Today, on the 175th anniversary of his birth, we honored him with a new plaque near his dormitory room in North Hall.

It's shaping up to be a four-star day in Madison, Wis. 

Want more? We're on Instagram at http://instagram.com/UWMadison. Tag your own photos to #UWMadison.

Welcome to your new office: meeting and working outside can make you happier and more productive. Take advantage of the new outdoor hotspots popping up on campus, like the rooftop patio at Nancy Nicholas Hall: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21889 

Which of these locations looks best to you?

Happening now: Thousands of #Badgers are nervously awaiting the start of Wisconsin Football's student season ticket sale. Last year, it lasted just 30 minutes before selling out. 

Are you in? Tell us about your seats!
#HappyFathersDay, #Badgers! How are you celebrating today?

Slow clap for Wisconsin Badgers track & field Coach Ed Nuttycombe, who announced his retirement today. 

In 30 years, he amassed 26 Big Ten Conference titles, won the 2007 NCAA Indoor Championship, and helped guide cross country to another 26 crowns. 

That's unparalleled success. Thanks for everything, Ed. #onwisconsin

How do you help a child whose parent is in prison? The team behind Sesame Street is tackling this issue with help from psychologist and UW-Madison Professor Julie Poehlmann. Poehlmann advised the show on the creation of special materials to help kids with incarcerated parents, including a new character named Alex whose dad is in prison: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21877

Seen these chalkboards near State Street? The city of Madison is partnering with UW to redevelop State Street and Library Mall, and anyone is welcome to submit their own "colorful" ideas for what to add: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21868

If you were in charge of reconstruction, what would you add to State Street or Library Mall?

It's June and we're welcoming all of our #FutureBadgers, along with UW First-Year Experience.

Good luck to '06 MFA grad Carrie Coon at tonight's Tony Awards! She's nominated for Best Performance by an Actress in a Featured Role in a Play for her portrayal of Honey in "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" Read more about her time at Wisconsin and on Broadway: http://go.wisc.edu/coon

You know the library, but do you know the real Helen C. White? White, who died on this day in 1967, was the first female professor in the UW-Madison College of Letters & Science and a world-renowned education expert. Here's a 1966 clip of her doing what she did best: http://go.wisc.edu/helenc

What's your favorite fact about Helen C. White?

The ultimate walk-in closet: the Helen Louise Allen Textile Collection, which boasts over 13,000 historically significant textile pieces, finds a new home in a climate-controlled, dust-proof section of Nancy Nicholas Hall. Items will be available for viewing once all unpacking is finished: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21857

What item from this collection would you like to see in your own wardrobe?

Madison has been gray and rainy of late, but this Spring has had a few brilliant days. 

Download this photo for your own cover and check out our best images at http://instagram.com/uwmadison.

A treat for those who live gluten-free: UW food science students have perfected "Wochi," a gluten-free, chocolate waffle with raspberry filling. The waffle is so tasty that it has advanced to the finals of a national food competition sponsored by Mars, Inc. Read more about Wochi here: http://www.news.wisc.edu/21831

What's the next snack idea that you'd like to see our team of food scientists cook up?

Housing assignments for the 2013-14 school year started rolling out tonight and future Badgers are lighting up Twitter, pledging their loyalty to #TeamLakeshore and #TeamSoutheast. The competition is close, so we wanted to hear from you. Which neighborhood is truly the best, and why?

Need a boost? Visit your Facebook profile. According to a study UW-Madison assistant professor of communication arts Catalina Toma, spending just a few minutes looking at your own Facebook can cause a significant increase in self-esteem. Read more here: go.wisc.edu/boost
Spotted outside The Wisconsin Union: a Badger act of kindness. Great work, guys! Now we know who to call if any SOAR visitors get lost on campus.

"You are you and no one else is. That's your potential value. You just need to figure out how to apply it." 

Anders Holm says that he barely got into UW-Madison and was lucky to get out, but we think he picked up a few pieces of wisdom along the way. In his charge to the 2013 graduates, the Workaholics star shared his advice on how to love rejection, get what you want, and trick people into thinking you can give a good commencement address.

Breakthrough moment: Our massive ice telescope in the Antarctica, the  IceCube Neutrino Observatory, has discovered evidence of extraterrestrial neutrinos.

The particles can carry information about the workings of the highest-energy and most distant phenomena in the universe. Learn more: http://go.wisc.edu/icecube
It's early May but it seems like summer at the Terrace. 80 degrees with a storm rolling in. We'll take it over snow!

For the Badgers out there who are just getting started with a long night of studying, Charlotte the French Bulldog is here to help. She visited College Library today with Dogs on Call, one of many cool stress relievers planned to help you #studystrong! Check out @college_library on Instagram and Twitter for updates.

Wisconsin Badgers steeplechase star Alex Brill delivered his gift on Saturday, making his mother Janis very proud by winning the Big Ten Outdoor Championships crown.

Best of luck to everyone with 7:45 a.m. Sunday exams. What are your tips on powering through to the end?

You may be aware that Interim Chancellor Ward is English. Did you also know that he's the biggest Manchester United fan on campus? 

Legendary United manager Sir Alex Ferguson's retirement announcement is sweeping headlines across the UK. Think of Sir Alex as Vince Lombardi + Phil Jackson + 27 years as the most successful manager in British football.

A Manchester native and passionate United supporter, Chancellor Ward shares his thoughts on Sir Alex and the future of the world's biggest soccer franchise.

Before we start with exams, we want to know: What's the single most important thing you've learned this semester?

Wisconsin Softball has quietly racked up its best season ever. Today, more than 2,000 fans came out to see the Badgers split a double-header with the  Michigan State Spartans and earn a program record 39th win!

Have you been out to the Goodman Diamond this season?

It's Kentucky Derby Day and we're pulling for Oxbow. 

The odds are against him, but this horse is trained by one of the best: Four-time Derby winner and '57 UW grad D. Wayne Lukas. Make your "Old Wisconsin Home" proud!

 What would you name your Derby horse?

At a Thursday ceremony in the Rose Garden, President Barack Obama had kind words for UW's incoming Chancellor Rebecca Blank. Blank has been serving as the acting secretary of the Department of Commerce.

"Becky is going to be taking on a pretty big job -- making sure those Badgers behave up in Wisconsin. And we know she's going to be extraordinary leading that institution."

Forget the baking soda volcanoes‚Äîtalented Madison-area middle school students are conducting their own experiments with stem cells at Wisconsin Institutes for Discovery. Right now they're researching different agents that could be used to treat heart disease. http://www.news.wisc.edu/21745

status_message: What's it look like out there? For the benefit of our friends near and far, we invite you to share winter storm photos from around campus on a new Flickr group we have created. We'll highlight some as the day proceeds. (Just join the group and then you can add photos to it.)

Updates to UW-Madison operations are being posted to wisc.edu. Campus streets are passable, but all asked to use extreme caution, avoid travel. As you know, classes are cancelled and non-essential employees should not report for work.
UW-Madison is cancelling Wednesday classes on account of the snow. All non-essential employees are being asked to stay home. Visit wisc.edu for details as they're available.
The weather forecast is calling for 10 to 16 inches of snow in the Madison area by tomorrow evening. Check the university home page for updates as the storm plays out.
